.TH strchrnul 3 (date) "Linux man-pages (unreleased)"
.SH NAME
strchrnul \- string search character or NUL
.SH LIBRARY
Standard C library
.RI ( libc ,\~ \-lc )
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.BR "#define _GNU_SOURCE" "  /* See feature_test_macros(7) */"
.B #include <string.h>
.P
.BI "char *strchrnul(const char *" s ", int " c );
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.BR strchrnul ()
function is like
.BR strchr (3)
except that if
.I c
is not found in
.IR s ,
then it returns a pointer to the null byte
at the end of
.IR s .
.P
It is equivalent to both of the following expressions:
.P
.in +4n
.EX
strchr(s, c) ?: strnul(s)
s + strcspn(s, (char [2]){c, \[aq]\[rs]0\[aq]})
.EE
.in
.SH RETURN VALUE
The
.BR strchrnul ()
function returns a pointer to the matched character,
or a pointer to the null byte at the end of
.I s
if the character is not found.
